A '''teal organisation''' is an emerging organisational [[paradigm]] that advocates a level of [[consciousness]] including all previous [[world view]]s within the operations of an [[organization|organisation]]. The concept of teal organisation refers to the next stage in the evolution of [[consciousness]] and was introduced in 2014 by [[Frederic Laloux]] in his book on [[Reinventing Organizations]].<ref name="lalouxfred-book">{{cite book | title= Reinventing Organizations: A Guide to Creating Organizations Inspired by the Next Stage of Human Consciousness |url= http://www.reinventingorganizations.com/ | location = |last= Laloux |first = Frederic |date = 2014 | publisher = Nelson Parker |page= 381 |isbn= 978-2960133509 }}</ref><ref name=stratbusy>{{cite web|title= The Future of Management Is Teal |url= https://www.strategy-business.com/article/00344?gko=10921 |website= Strategy + Business |date= July 6, 2015 |accessdate= }}</ref> It also rests on previous studies done by [[Evolutionary psychology|evolutionary]] and [[Social psychology|social psychologists]] including [[Jean Gebser]], [[Clare W. Graves]], [[Don Edward Beck]], Chris Cowan and [[Ken Wilbur|Ken Wilber]] who explored the stages of development and impact of human consciousness.<ref>[http://www.clarewgraves.com/articles_content/1974_Futurist/1974_Futurist.html "Human Nature Prepares for a Momentous Leap"], by Clare W. Graves, in ''The Futurist'', 1974</ref><ref>[http://www.clarewgraves.com/articles_content/1974_Futurist/Futr74_tbl.pdf "Charted Levels of Existence as seen by Clare W. Graves"], in ''The Futurist'', 1974</ref><ref>{{cite book |authors=[[Ken Wilber]] |title=The Spectrum of Consciousness |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publ. |year=2002 |isbn=978-81-208-1848-4|pages=3–16}}</ref>
== Overview == A teal organisation transcends and integrates the existing limitations of current static organisational paradigms including Amber, Orange and Green organisations.<ref name=huffpost1>{{cite news |title= Reinventing Management, Part 1: What Color Is Your Organization? |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/great-work-cultures/reinventing-management-pa_b_9387286.html |newspaper= [[HuffPost|Huffington Post]] |last= Collins |first= Rod |date= March 4, 2016 |accessdate= }}</ref> It is characterized by three [[Epiphany (feeling)|breakthroughs]] in human [[collaboration]], specific to this evolutionary level: ''self-management'' suggests a system based on peer relationships with no need for hierarchy, consensus, nor central command and control; ''wholeness'' is about a consistent set of practices that invite members to reclaim their inner wholeness and bring on the workplace “all of who they are”;<ref name=futureconsid1>{{cite web |title= What does Wholeness mean in the context of Teal Organising? |url= https://futureconsiderations.com/wholeness-in-the-context-of-teal/ |website= Future Considerations |date= July 7, 2015 |accessdate= }}</ref> ''evolutionary purpose'' introduces a teal organisation as a living [[organism]] with a direction of its own where its members are invited to listen and take note of the purpose it wants to serve. These breakthroughs overcome the limitations of previous organisational models in that they welcome the emotional, intuitive, and spiritual elements in lieu of the usual display of rationality, determination and strength; and concealment of doubts or vulnerability.<ref>{{cite web|title= The Most Dangerous Notion in "Reinventing Organizations" |url= https://medium.com/@jessicajprentice/the-most-dangerous-notion-in-reinventing-organizations-9032930295e2 |date= July 6, 2015 |publisher= [[Medium (website)|Medium Corporation]] |author= Jessica Prentice}}</ref> During its evolution, a teal organisation exhibits properties similar to [[complex adaptive system]]s because the interactions and relationships between its elements are [[Nonlinear system|nonlinear]] and based on few simple rules or guiding principles. These elements learn from the past and their immediate environment and then adapt accordingly for the survival of the system.<ref>{{cite thesis |last= Andersson |first= Malin|date= 2015 |title=Exploring the latest paradigm shift in organizational consciousness development, by using the framework from Reinventing Organizations |type= Master thesis|chapter= |publisher= |docket= |oclc= |url= http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.835.4680&rep=rep1&type=pdf |access-date=}}</ref> A number of notable organisations around the world has adopted and operates on the teal organisation model<ref>{{cite web |title= The Design Principles evolve "naturally" in the workplace and the need for a scientific foundation |url= https://www.prosocial.world/post/the-design-principles-evolve-naturally-in-the-workplace-and-the-need-for-a-scientific-foundation |publisher= Prosocial World |date= June 2, 2017 |accessdate= }}</ref> including [[The Morning Star Company]] (food processing, United States),<ref name=morningself>{{cite web|title= The Morning Star Company - Self-Management |url= http://morningstarco.com/index.cgi?Page=Self-Management |website= morningstarco.com |date= |accessdate= }}</ref> [[Patagonia (clothing)|Patagonia]] (apparel, United States), [[Sounds True]] (media, United States), AES (energy sector, international), [[Buurtzorg Nederland]] (health care, Netherlands), ESBZ ([[K–12]] school, Germany), Heiligenfelde (mental health hospitals, Germany), [[Nucor]] (steel manufacturing, international).
